			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">At any rate.. you should always write to every register once to set it to a known state.  Never leave registers uninitialized (unless they are going unused... like an IRQ counter you have disabled -- however nothing like that is the case for MMC1, so you should write to everything)</div><br />I thought SNROM (MMC1, CHR RAM, PRG &lt;= 256 KiB) in 8 KiB mode left registers $A000 and $C000 unused.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">1)  Make sure your Reset vector points to somewhere in the last 16K of PRG ($C000-FFFF).  You cannot assume any specific page will be swapped into $8000-BFFF</div>
<br />And some MMC1 chip revisions don't even guarantee that the mapper powers on in fixed-$C000 mode; it could start in 32 KiB mode or fixed-$8000 mode. For these, you have to put the vectors and a reset stub as the last 16 bytes of every PRG bank:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">.segment &quot;FFF0STUB&quot;<br /><br />; Reset the MMC1 and set the stack pointer.<br />; The 'reset' routine will take care of initializing<br />; the rest of the NES.<br />fff0stub:<br />&nbsp; sei<br />&nbsp; ldx #$FF<br />&nbsp; stx fff0stub<br />&nbsp; txs<br />&nbsp; jmp reset<br />&nbsp; .addr nmi, fff0stub, irq<br /><br />.segment &quot;CODE&quot;<br />reset:<br />&nbsp; lda #0<br />&nbsp; sta $2000<br />&nbsp; sta $2001<br />&nbsp; ; and init the rest of the registers &#40;omitted&#41;<br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

